The paper deals with a user interface for outbound translation, which involves human interaction with machine translation systems. This falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP), which is typically classified under cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also discusses the use of additional subsystems such as quality estimation, which could be considered as part of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The study involves human annotators, which suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The use cases mentioned in the paper involve communication with IT support and asking encyclopedic questions, which could be related to information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper discusses the evaluation of machine translation systems, which could be considered as part of machine learning (cs.LG).
